## Test Anti-Pattern Audit: `UserRepositoryTests`

**Summary: 3 Critical · 1 High · 1 Medium · 2 Low**

Three tests give completely false confidence — this directly explains your incident.

---

### 🔴 Critical — False confidence (fix immediately)

**1. No assertion — `GetUser_NonExistentId_ReturnsNull`**
The test retrieves a user and does nothing with it. It always passes.
```csharp
// ❌ Before
var user = repo.GetById(999);
// should be null

// ✅ After
var user = repo.GetById(999);
Assert.IsNull(user);
```

**2. Swallowed exception — `AddUser_DuplicateId_ThrowsException`**
If no exception is thrown, execution falls through and the test silently passes. The `try/catch` hides the failure.
```csharp
// ❌ Before
try
{
    repo.Add(new User(1, "Bob"));
}
catch (Exception) { return; }

// ✅ After
Assert.ThrowsException<InvalidOperationException>(() => repo.Add(new User(1, "Bob")));
```

**3. Always-true assertion — `DeleteUser_RemovesFromRepository`**
`Assert.AreEqual(repo.Count, repo.Count)` compares the value to itself — it can never fail.
```csharp
// ❌ Before
Assert.AreEqual(repo.Count, repo.Count);

// ✅ After
Assert.AreEqual(0, repo.Count);
```

---

### 🟠 High

**4. Broad exception type — `AddUser_NullUser_ThrowsArgumentNullException`**
Asserts `Exception` but the method name promises `ArgumentNullException`. Any unrelated crash would make this pass.
```csharp
// ❌ Before
Assert.ThrowsException<Exception>(() => repo.Add(null!));

// ✅ After
Assert.ThrowsException<ArgumentNullException>(() => repo.Add(null!));
```

---

### 🟡 Medium / 🔵 Low

| Severity | Test / Location | Issue |
|----------|----------------|-------|
| Medium | `UpdateUser_ChangesName` | **Weak assertion** — `user.Name != "Alice"` would pass if name were set to anything, even garbage. Assert `Assert.AreEqual("Alicia", user.Name)` instead. |
| Low | Class field `_client` | **Unused `HttpClient`** — static, never used, never disposed. Remove it. |
| Low | `SearchUsers_ByPartialName` | **Leftover `Console.WriteLine`** — debugging output still present. |

---

### ✅ Positive observations

- `GetAllUsers_ReturnsCorrectCount` is well-structured with count + membership assertions
- Naming convention is consistent (`Method_Scenario_Expected`)
- Each test creates its own `UserRepository` — good isolation, no shared mutable state

---

### Priority

Fix the **3 Critical** items first — those are tests that pass regardless of whether the code works, which is exactly the class of bug that caused your incident. The High and Medium fixes are quick wins to do at the same time.
